                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Police-sergeant E</hi> 68.) I produce a certificate of the prisoner's conviction—(<hi rend="italic">Read: "Central Criminal Court, June, 1857; <persName id="t18600507-name-520">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-520" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-520" type="surname" value="SCAINES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-520" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>Henry Scaines</persName> convicted of receiving 272 handkerchiefs, and other goods. 
Confined One Year."</hi>) I was present—Scaines is the person—he was tried in 1859 for stealing a watch, and acquitted—he has been a constant associate of thieves to my knowledge—the Alma coffee-shop is a regular harbour for thieves—I think there is not a den like it in London.</p>
